[{"id":"VR025151-22","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<p class=\"standalone_statement style:1\">This question is a long free-response question. Show your work for each part of the question.</p>\n\n<p class=\"standalone_statement style:1\">(12 points, suggested time 25 minutes)</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram consisting of three figures. Each figure consists of two insulating spheres, each of which are suspended vertically from a rod that has a pivot at the top. There is a note that Figure 1 is not drawn to scale. In Figure 1, both rods are vertical. Both spheres are labeled m comma positive Q sub 0. In Figure 2, both rods are vertical. The sphere are a horizontal distance of r sub 2 from one another. In Figure 3, the rod on the left slants downward and to the left from its pivot, and the rod on the right slants downward and to the right from its pivot. The pivots are a horizontal distance of r sub 2 from one another, and the spheres are a horizontal distance of r sub 3 from one another. The distance r sub 3 appears to be greater than the distance r sub 2.\" height=\"189\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR025151.g05.png\" width=\"585\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Two insulating spheres with mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m\"><math alttext=\"m\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive Q sub 0\"><math alttext=\"positive Q sub 0\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> are near Earth’s surface, suspended vertically from identical light, stiff rods with pivots at the top, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The spheres are initially far apart. The pivots are locked so the rods remain vertical while the spheres are moved together by external forces until the spheres are a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r sub 2\"><math alttext=\"r sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> from each other, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Finally, the pivots are held a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r sub 2\"><math alttext=\"r sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> apart and unlocked, and the rods are allowed to swing out until the spheres momentarily come to rest a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r sub 3\"><math alttext=\"r sub 3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> apart, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The pivots are always at the same height.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) Consider the system that includes only the two spheres, with Earth external to the system.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">i. Write an expression for the work done moving the spheres horizontally from far apart to a separation of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r sub 2\"><math alttext=\"r sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Express your answer in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q sub 0\"><math alttext=\"Q sub 0\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"r sub 2\"><math alttext=\"r sub 2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, and physical constants, as appropriate.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">ii. The total energy of the two-sphere system (with Earth still external to the system) changes as the system goes from the configuration in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> to the configuration in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Explain how the energy changes in terms of the forces exerted on the system.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"id":"VR025151-22","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) Now consider the system that contains both Earth and the two spheres. What is the work done on this new system for the changes in sphere position described in parts (a)(i) and (ii) ? Explain your reasoning.</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a blank space, with two headings. The heading on the left is “Part (a)(i).” The heading on the right is “Part (a)(ii).”\" height=\"22\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR025151.g02.png\" width=\"450\" /></div>\n</div>\n"},{"id":"VR025151-22","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) The rods are now held fixed at the positions shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, and negative charge is added to the right sphere so its net charge is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative Q sub 0\"><math alttext=\"negative Q sub 0\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The circles in the figure below represent the spheres. On the figure, do the following.</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li class=\"list_paragraph\">Draw a single vector originating on point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> that represents the net electric field at that point.</li>\n\t<li class=\"list_paragraph\">For each of the dots on the horizontal daashed line, draw an isoline of electric potential that goes through the dot.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram of two spheres along a horizontal dashed line. The sphere on the left is labeled positive Q sub 0, and the sphere on the right is labeled negative Q sub 0. There are three points indicated on the horizontal line, between the two spheres. One point is just to the right of the sphere labeled positive Q sub 0. One point is about halfway between the two spheres. One point is about halfway between the other two points. A point labeled P is indicated directly above the sphere labeled negative Q sub 0.\" height=\"95\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR025151.g06.png\" width=\"330\" /></div>\n</div>\n"},{"id":"VR025151-22","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) In a new situation, the two spheres still have the same mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"m\"><math alttext=\"m\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, but the left sphere is made of plastic and has charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive Q sub P\"><math alttext=\"positive Q sub P\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>p</mtext></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and the right sphere is made of metal and is uncharged. The spheres are brought near but do not touch, as shown below on the left. When the rods are allowed to pivot, the spheres move toward each other, as shown on the right. In terms of charge distributions, explain why the force between the spheres is attractive.</p>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram consisting of two figures. Each figure consists of two insulating spheres, each of which are suspended vertically from a rod that has a pivot at the top. In the first figure, both rods are vertical. The left sphere is labeled “Plastic, m comma positive Q sub P,” and the right sphere is labeled “Metal, m comma Uncharged.” In the second figure, the rod on the left slants downward and to the right from its pivot, and the rod on the right slants downward and to the left from its pivot. The distance between the pivots appears to be greater than the distance between the spheres.\" height=\"103\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR025151.g07.png\" width=\"430\" /></div>\n</div>\n"}]